Is this to do with Larry?

211
00:11:28,788 --> 00:11:31,450
That would be your husband,
Lawrence Seaver?

212
00:11:31,524 --> 00:11:35,858
- Raymond's father?
- He hasn't answered his cell phone in days.

213
00:11:35,928 --> 00:11:38,988
I've left so many messages.
Please come in.

214
00:11:40,633 --> 00:11:42,897
- <i>[Woman On TV] Meerkats form...</i>
- Ray, honey.

215
00:11:42,968 --> 00:11:45,903
- We have company.
- Who's she?

216
00:11:45,971 --> 00:11:48,963
- Did they find Daddy?
- My name is Temperance, Ray.

217
00:11:49,041 --> 00:11:51,441
And I'm just here
to ask a few questions.

218
00:11:53,012 --> 00:11:56,311
- Your husband's been missing since...
- <i>Thursday.</i>

219
00:11:56,382 --> 00:12:00,341
We didn't think of him as missing. He left
on his business trip like he does every week.

220
00:12:00,419 --> 00:12:02,819
But he never fails
to at least call us back.

221
00:12:02,888 --> 00:12:06,847
- That must've hurt.
- Not so much. I'm used to it.

222
00:12:06,926 --> 00:12:10,794
Ray has brittle bone.
It's just a mild form, though, like Larry's.

223
00:12:10,863 --> 00:12:13,923
- You think I could sign your cast?
- Sure. I'll get a pen.

224
00:12:19,205 --> 00:12:21,503
Mrs. Seaver, I need
to borrow this photo.

225
00:12:21,574 --> 00:12:24,441
Okay. Why?

226
00:12:24,510 --> 00:12:27,707
Well, we found a body.

227
00:12:27,780 --> 00:12:30,681
Oh, God.

228
00:12:33,252 --> 00:12:35,311
Sorry I couldn't do more.

229
00:12:35,387 --> 00:12:38,413
Skullcap was falling apart
faster than I could put a face on it.

230
00:12:38,491 --> 00:12:41,619
I'm not sure we'd have a match
either way with so little to work with.

231
00:12:41,694 --> 00:12:43,992
Okay, here we go.
Got our guy.

232
00:12:44,063 --> 00:12:45,997
- What?
- Mother and her daughter up in Maryland.

233
00:12:46,065 --> 00:12:47,999
Dad missing since Thursday.

234
00:12:49,802 --> 00:12:54,136
- Who's that?
- Mother and son down in Virginia.

235
00:12:54,206 --> 00:12:56,572
<i>Father missing since Thursday.</i>

236
00:12:56,642 --> 00:13:00,874
<i>Whoa. Mine's Lawrence Turner, 35,</i>
<i>commercial electrician.</i>

237
00:13:00,946 --> 00:13:03,915
- Oh...
- And I've got Lawrence Seaver, 35.

238
00:13:03,983 --> 00:13:06,474
- my...
- Commercial electrician.

239
00:13:06,552 --> 00:13:09,851
- God.
- I think old Larry's got two wives.

240
00:13:09,922 --> 00:13:12,823
More like two lives.

241
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:23,764
Just make sureJenny takes her meds.

242
00:13:23,836 --> 00:13:26,327
And tell her Mommy
will see her in the morning.

243
00:13:27,506 --> 00:13:29,497
<i>Thanks, Betty.</i>

244
00:13:31,210 --> 00:13:35,146
- How old's your daughter?
- Six and a half.

245
00:13:35,214 --> 00:13:37,512
She and Larry,
they have a special bond.

246
00:13:37,583 --> 00:13:40,950
- Brittle bone.
- You know about that?

247
00:13:41,020 --> 00:13:42,715
She's type I
like your husband?

248
00:13:42,788 --> 00:13:46,224
He's always felt
so guilty about that.

249
00:13:46,292 --> 00:13:48,817
He really dotes on her,
on both of us.

250
00:13:48,894 --> 00:13:52,557
<i>Mrs. Turner, your husband</i>
<i>ever talk about any conflicts at work?</i>

251
00:13:52,631 --> 00:13:55,725
Never.
Everyone loves Larry.

252
00:13:55,801 --> 00:13:58,770
He's fun, smart, hardworking.

253
00:13:58,838 --> 00:14:01,102
<i>That's what keeps him</i>
<i>out of town so much.</i>

254
00:14:01,173 --> 00:14:03,107
Yeah, about that...

255
00:14:03,175 --> 00:14:07,077
I didn't realize electricians were called upon
to be away from home so much.

256
00:14:07,146 --> 00:14:11,105
There's just so much underbidding.
And it's not like we can get by on what I make.

257
00:14:11,183 --> 00:14:14,710
- As?
- I teach. Eighth-grade science.

258
00:14:14,787 --> 00:14:17,915
- Got it.
- So he has to travel.

259
00:14:17,990 --> 00:14:22,086
- <i>Go where the money is.</i>
<i>Not that he ever complains.</i>
- [Clears Throat]

260
00:14:22,161 --> 00:14:26,291
<i>It makes coming home to us</i>
<i>all the more sweeter, he says.</i>

261
00:14:26,365 --> 00:14:29,459
<i>Oh, God!</i>
<i>What are we gonna do?</i>

262
00:14:29,535 --> 00:14:32,834
Will you just excuse me
for one moment.

263
00:14:32,905 --> 00:14:35,100
I'm so sorry.
[Clears Throat]

264
00:14:41,180 --> 00:14:43,307
These women have to know
the truth about their husbands.

265
00:14:43,382 --> 00:14:45,179
- They could be in cahoots.
- Cahoots?

266
00:14:45,251 --> 00:14:48,743
If they somehow found out that Larry was
two-timing them, they could both want him dead.

267
00:14:48,821 --> 00:14:51,346
- Okay, so what now? We ask them?
- No, no, no, no, no.

268
00:14:51,423 --> 00:14:53,414
It's all taken care of.

269
00:14:55,995 --> 00:14:58,327
Mrs. Turner, could you please
come with me?

270
00:14:58,397 --> 00:15:01,264
Right this way. Just wait here
in the visitors' lounge.

271
00:15:01,333 --> 00:15:04,427
We won't be long. Help yourself
to a cup of coffee.

272
00:15:04,503 --> 00:15:07,097
Thank you.

273
00:15:07,172 --> 00:15:09,663
- That's the interrogation room.
- Not tonight.

274
00:15:15,748 --> 00:15:19,013
Hmm, nice touch
with the kitty posters.

275
00:15:19,084 --> 00:15:21,109
- Who are you talking to?
- That couple in there.

276
00:15:21,186 --> 00:15:23,552
<i>Agent Curry and Moran.</i>
<i>They set up the room.</i>

277
00:15:23,622 --> 00:15:25,954
I'll never drink
F.B.I. coffee again.

278
00:15:26,025 --> 00:15:29,153
- <i>[Phone Beeps]</i>
- Whenever you're ready, Charlie.

279
00:15:32,765 --> 00:15:34,733
You know, I almost
married her, you know?

280
00:15:36,568 --> 00:15:40,527
- Agent Curry?
- Rebecca. My ex.

281
00:15:40,606 --> 00:15:42,870
Oh. You can talk about her now.

282
00:15:42,942 --> 00:15:44,967
Yeah, she got pregnant.

283
00:15:45,044 --> 00:15:47,877
I wanted to do the right thing,
but, you know, she said no.

284
00:15:47,947 --> 00:15:51,178
You've told me this before.
Not that you've ever said why.

285
00:15:51,250 --> 00:15:53,309
Well, issues with my job.

286
00:15:53,385 --> 00:15:56,877
She wanted to start her own career.
She wanted to finish graduate school.

287
00:15:56,956 --> 00:15:58,651
Alone with a baby?

288
00:15:58,724 --> 00:16:01,750
Logic. Right?
You're applying logic?

289
00:16:01,827 --> 00:16:05,763
- Do you still love her?
- Not... like I did. Not like that.

290
00:16:05,831 --> 00:16:07,389
Then why can't it just be sex?

291
00:16:07,466 --> 00:16:10,264
There's nothing "just"
about sex, Bones.

292
00:16:10,336 --> 00:16:12,270
But all mammals need it.

293
00:16:12,338 --> 00:16:15,830
That release of serotonin.
The rush of endorphins.

294
00:16:15,908 --> 00:16:19,844
Naturally, you seek it with
someone with whom you share a sexual rapport.

295
00:16:19,912 --> 00:16:21,903
Rapport, right.
That's the word.

296
00:16:21,981 --> 00:16:23,915
I know when I'm in need
of a release...

297
00:16:23,983 --> 00:16:27,851
there's a former partner or two
I'm... sure I could call.

298
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:30,514
Okay, Bones. Thanks so much.
I feel so much better now, huh?

299
00:16:30,589 --> 00:16:32,580
Here we go.

300
00:16:32,658 --> 00:16:34,626
[Over Speaker]
Help yourself to coffee, Mrs. Seaver.

301
00:16:41,834 --> 00:16:45,600
<i>Oh, I get it.</i>
<i>Very smart.</i>

302
00:16:45,671 --> 00:16:49,437
Well, it's my job, Bones.
It's, you know, what I do for a living.

303
00:16:51,343 --> 00:16:54,972
They don't seem like...
Wait.

304
00:17:00,786 --> 00:17:04,620
<i>Hmm, they may as well be</i>
<i>in separate rooms.</i>

305
00:17:04,690 --> 00:17:08,490
Making them either great actresses
who are in cahoots...

306
00:17:08,560 --> 00:17:12,758
Or... they have no idea
what's going on.

307
00:17:18,337 --> 00:17:20,396
How could these women not know?

308
00:17:20,472 --> 00:17:22,440
Brennan was pretty sure
that they didn't.

309
00:17:22,508 --> 00:17:25,272
And still don't apparently.
Booth wants to wait to tell them.

310
00:17:25,344 --> 00:17:29,007
- Wait for what? To summon the nerve?
- <i>Maybe.</i>

311
00:17:29,081 --> 00:17:31,311
I just wouldn't want these women
finding out at the funeral.

312
00:17:31,383 --> 00:17:33,647
I'll take a front row seat for that.

313
00:17:34,653 --> 00:17:37,451
Sorry. Did I say that out loud?

314
00:17:37,523 --> 00:17:40,356
Have you found anything resembling
a weapon in the tub yet?

315
00:17:40,426 --> 00:17:42,360
Not yet. Why?

316
00:17:42,428 --> 00:17:44,259
<i>These skull fragments may feel</i>
<i>like wet cardboard...</i>

317
00:17:44,329 --> 00:17:46,422
but I'm pretty sure we're
looking at blunt force trauma.

318
00:17:46,498 --> 00:17:49,126
<i>I'll second that.</i>
<i>Roughly "V"-shaped.</i>

319
00:17:49,201 --> 00:17:50,862
Corner of a 2-by-4 maybe?

320
00:17:50,936 --> 00:17:54,702
Specks of blood at the point of impact.
Could've been the lethal blow.

321
00:17:54,773 --> 00:17:58,607
Making him dead before
he was doused with lye. Oh, happy day.

322
00:17:58,677 --> 00:18:00,872
<i>I've isolated</i>
<i>our corrosive culprits.</i>

323
00:18:00,946 --> 00:18:05,007
Sodium hypochlorite, calcium hypochlorite,
and hydrochloric acid.

324
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:08,212
- Available at your local market.
- Lucky the whole tub didn't explode.

325
00:18:08,287 --> 00:18:10,221
It practically did.
Along with teeth...

326
00:18:10,289 --> 00:18:13,850
I keep finding these
tiny shards of copper from the fixtures.

327
00:18:13,926 --> 00:18:16,656
Is that what this is?

328
00:18:16,728 --> 00:18:19,458
<i>No. That would be a wedding band.</i>

329
00:18:19,531 --> 00:18:21,726
Braided gold and platinum.

330
00:18:21,800 --> 00:18:23,734
Preserved by true love, no doubt.

331
00:18:23,802 --> 00:18:26,396
- One metal for each desperate housewife.
- <i>People...</i>

332
00:18:26,472 --> 00:18:28,303
can we at least fake
some sense of decorum?

333
00:18:28,373 --> 00:18:30,967
<i>I can't help it.</i>
<i>It's so</i> Jerry Springer.

334
00:18:31,043 --> 00:18:34,444
<i>First of all, how does</i>
<i>anyonejuggle two spouses?</i>

335
00:18:34,513 --> 00:18:37,607
<i>I can think of ways. Of course,</i>
<i>byjuggle, I mean quite literally...</i>

336
00:18:37,683 --> 00:18:39,651
I have a scalpel.

337
00:18:39,718 --> 00:18:42,687
Maybe he dissolved himself so there'd
be more of him to go around.

338
00:18:42,754 --> 00:18:45,018
I'm going to hell, aren't I?

339
00:18:45,090 --> 00:18:47,081
I'll save you a seat.

340
00:18:51,430 --> 00:18:53,227
<i>Oh, no.</i>
<i>Not sweet Mr. Seaver!</i>

341
00:18:53,298 --> 00:18:55,232
- It can't be him.
- Yeah.

342
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:57,427
Well, um, is that
your boss in there?

343
00:18:57,503 --> 00:19:00,336
I mean, who would do something like that?
Everybody loves the man.

344
00:19:00,405 --> 00:19:02,202
Well, you know, not everyone.

345
00:19:02,274 --> 00:19:04,265
Hey, what's goin' on?

346
00:19:04,343 --> 00:19:06,436
- Mr. Valero, you won't believe it.
- Agent Booth. We met yesterday.

347
00:19:06,512 --> 00:19:08,878
<i>It was Mr. Seaver.</i>
<i>That's who was in the bathtub.</i>

348
00:19:08,947 --> 00:19:11,347
Wait. Larry?
The electrician?

349
00:19:11,416 --> 00:19:14,681
- Yeah. Larry the electrician. Now...
- Son of a bitch!

350
00:19:14,753 --> 00:19:16,778
Now I'm never gonna see my money.

351
00:19:21,026 --> 00:19:23,017
You know, I must say, uh, Pete...

352
00:19:23,095 --> 00:19:26,462
<i>you're the first person I've come across</i>
<i>who's ever had a bad word to say about Larry.</i>

353
00:19:26,532 --> 00:19:29,558
Well, the guy does have
a way with people. Or he did.

354
00:19:29,635 --> 00:19:32,934
- I mean, I liked him too before he got all slippery.
- Slippery?

355
00:19:33,005 --> 00:19:36,532
I fronted the guy 85 grand
to cover electrical supplies.

356
00:19:36,608 --> 00:19:40,772
Last week, I got the inspector walking around,
and she cites me for cheap materials.

357
00:19:40,846 --> 00:19:43,747
Substandard circuit breakers,
insufficient G.F.I.'s.

358
00:19:43,815 --> 00:19:46,477
- Where'd the 85 grand go?
- Exactly what I asked Larry.

359
00:19:46,552 --> 00:19:49,385
"Show me receipts," I said.
What do I get?

360
00:19:49,454 --> 00:19:52,116
<i>Sob stories ofbad bookkeeping...</i>

361
00:19:52,191 --> 00:19:54,125
his son's health,
problems with the wife.

362
00:19:54,193 --> 00:19:55,956
His wife?

363
00:19:56,028 --> 00:19:59,327
Yeah. Like I don't got a wife of my own, right?
[Chuckles]

364
00:19:59,398 --> 00:20:02,265
<i>You know, you realize, Pete,</i>
<i>that everything that you're telling me...</i>

365
00:20:02,334 --> 00:20:05,826
- sounds a lot like motive.
- [Scoffs]

366
00:20:05,904 --> 00:20:07,895
Great.
Do I need a lawyer?

367
00:20:07,973 --> 00:20:10,100
I don't know.
You tell me.

368
00:20:11,243 --> 00:20:13,177
All right, look.

369
00:20:13,245 --> 00:20:15,839
I can't say that I wasn't angry enough
to want the guy dead.

370
00:20:15,914 --> 00:20:19,577
<i>But like always, I fell back on</i>
<i>the old builders' code.</i>

371
00:20:19,651 --> 00:20:22,245
- "Can't squeeze money from the dead man?"
- You know it.

372
00:20:22,321 --> 00:20:25,347
Well, you know, as codes go,
it's hardly limited to builders.

373
00:20:25,424 --> 00:20:28,450
No, no, no. It's our code.
You can look it up.

374
00:20:28,527 --> 00:20:30,119
No, no.
Maybe later.

375
00:20:30,195 --> 00:20:33,858
Hey, you wouldn't happen to have
any of Larry's old paperwork on file?

376
00:20:33,932 --> 00:20:36,162
- <i>Accounts? Receipts?</i>
- Yeah, yeah. Sure.

377
00:20:39,838 --> 00:20:41,897
<i>[Chattering]</i>

378
00:20:45,444 --> 00:20:49,005
<i>I think I've stumbled</i>
<i>upon an anomaly, Dr. Saroyan.</i>

379
00:20:49,081 --> 00:20:51,447
It looks like
a splintered ulna bone.

380
00:20:51,516 --> 00:20:55,384
- <i>But it's not. It's ivory.</i>
- From the tusk of a small elephant?

381
00:20:55,454 --> 00:21:00,551
I was hoping you'd know.
If you notice these indentations here.

382
00:21:00,626 --> 00:21:04,722
Like teeth marks on a pencil.
See what Angela can make of it.

383
00:21:04,796 --> 00:21:08,994
<i>And after that, I'll need you to go back to</i>
<i>the crime scene with the photos I'm taking.</i>

384
00:21:09,067 --> 00:21:12,161
See what you can find with the approximate
shape and dimension of this blunt force wound.

385
00:21:12,237 --> 00:21:15,138
- Like a murder weapon?
- It needn't look like one.

386
00:21:15,207 --> 00:21:17,038
Anything that replicates
this pattern.

387
00:21:18,477 --> 00:21:21,071
- I'm going on police business.
- So proud.

388
00:21:21,146 --> 00:21:23,137
Wait, does he mean out?
In the world?

389
00:21:23,215 --> 00:21:26,082
We'll pin our phone number on his shirt.
What's that you got there?

390
00:21:26,151 --> 00:21:28,551
Well, having finally hit
the very bottom of the tub...

391
00:21:28,620 --> 00:21:33,353
I found it plugged with a ceramic stopper,
which I lifted and voilà.

392
00:21:33,425 --> 00:21:35,791
What do you make of this?

393
00:21:36,995 --> 00:21:39,088
<i>Bones...[Laughs]</i>
<i>are you ready for this?</i>

394
00:21:39,164 --> 00:21:41,223
- Did you tell the wives yet?
- No, not yet.

395
00:21:41,300 --> 00:21:44,064
But I did some checking into
two-time Larry's finances.

396
00:21:44,136 --> 00:21:47,628
Under the last name Seaver, he's got
a half-a-million-dollar life insurance policy.

397
00:21:47,706 --> 00:21:50,504
- Assigning motive to Gayle Seaver.
- Under the last name Turner...

398
00:21:50,575 --> 00:21:53,510
he's got a living will leaving everything
to Lila and their daughter.

399
00:21:53,578 --> 00:21:55,512
- Giving both women motive.
- Right.

400
00:21:55,580 --> 00:21:59,016
Which is just a matter of which one needed
the money more than they needed their Larry.

401
00:21:59,084 --> 00:22:01,552
- I might be able to help.
- With what?

402
00:22:01,620 --> 00:22:03,554
A very small used condom?

403
00:22:03,622 --> 00:22:05,817
It's the finger from a rubber glove.

404
00:22:05,891 --> 00:22:08,553
Hodgins just found it wedged
under the tub's drain stopper.

405
00:22:08,627 --> 00:22:11,187
Oh, it was spared
the corrosive effects of the lye.

406
00:22:11,263 --> 00:22:14,289
<i>Meaning, we may be able</i>
<i>to pull a fingerprint from the inside.</i>

407
00:22:14,366 --> 00:22:16,698
No maybes about it.
If there's a print, I'll pull it.

408
00:22:16,768 --> 00:22:19,965
- And <i>when</i> I pull it...
- We'll have our killer.

409
00:22:24,976 --> 00:22:26,910
It's just standard procedure, Lila.

410
00:22:26,978 --> 00:22:29,970
<i>Just press four fingers</i>
<i>firmly and hold.</i>

411
00:22:30,048 --> 00:22:32,812
Our investigation turned up
a print at the crime scene.

412
00:22:32,884 --> 00:22:37,548
<i>And wejust need yours, Gayle,</i>
<i>to avoid any possible confusion.</i>

413
00:22:39,324 --> 00:22:41,349
<i>This isn't gonna take long, is it?</i>

414
00:22:41,426 --> 00:22:43,690
- Our tech has the print you pulled?
- Ring finger, left hand.

415
00:22:43,762 --> 00:22:45,821
Then this shouldn't take long at all.
Just wait here.

416
00:22:45,897 --> 00:22:48,331
Wait. Are you sure
this is the best time to tell them?

417
00:22:48,400 --> 00:22:50,834
What does that mean? After two days
of nagging me, you're just...

418
00:22:50,902 --> 00:22:52,961
- Now you're getting cold feet?
- What? I do not nag.

419
00:22:53,038 --> 00:22:57,338
Well, you know, it's an anthropological
inevitability for women to gossip and nag.

420
00:22:57,409 --> 00:22:59,434
Can I get anyone a soda?

421
00:22:59,511 --> 00:23:03,072
No, thank you.
Are you on my husband's case too?

422
00:23:03,148 --> 00:23:05,082
No. I don't work here.

423
00:23:06,184 --> 00:23:08,948
You're the lady
from the waiting room.

424
00:23:09,020 --> 00:23:11,580
- <i>You gave me a tissue?</i>
- Oh, yeah.

425
00:23:11,656 --> 00:23:13,590
- <i>That was you?</i>
- Yeah.

426
00:23:13,658 --> 00:23:16,957
- Sorry. I'm a little out of it.
- Yeah. I know how that feels.

427
00:23:17,028 --> 00:23:18,962
Actually, ladies, let me make
some introductions.

428
00:23:19,030 --> 00:23:23,126
Uh, Gayle Seaver,
Lila Turner. Lila, Gayle.

429
00:23:23,201 --> 00:23:25,362
Hi. Lila, that was
very sweet of you. I...

430
00:23:25,437 --> 00:23:27,701
- I'd just lost my husband.
- You did?

431
00:23:27,773 --> 00:23:30,139
<i>So did I.</i>

432
00:23:30,208 --> 00:23:33,268
Actually, that's... why
you're both here really.

433
00:23:33,345 --> 00:23:37,281
Um, for the same reason,
for the same husband.

434
00:23:38,350 --> 00:23:40,784
- I'm sorry?
- Yeah. Me too.

435
00:23:40,852 --> 00:23:45,414
What Agent Booth's trying to say
is that your husbands, Larry...

436
00:23:45,490 --> 00:23:47,890
are the same Larry.

437
00:23:47,959 --> 00:23:51,326
<i>[Booth]</i>
<i>Uh, this will help.</i>

438
00:23:51,396 --> 00:23:53,921
A little show-and-tell. Um...

439
00:23:56,535 --> 00:23:59,197
Well, this is wrong.

440
00:23:59,271 --> 00:24:01,535
It's a joke.
A sick joke.

441
00:24:01,606 --> 00:24:04,131
- Actually, it's not...
- My Larry would never...

442
00:24:04,209 --> 00:24:06,143
- Your Larry? This is my Larry!
- My Larry!

443
00:24:06,211 --> 00:24:09,237
- He's my husband. What are you talking about?
- Just go ahead and lie like that?

444
00:24:09,314 --> 00:24:14,308
- Bones?
- Okay. Let's sit! Everyone just sit down.

445
00:24:14,386 --> 00:24:16,411
<i>[Lila] This is ridiculous.</i>

446
00:24:16,488 --> 00:24:18,251
Fine.

447
00:24:18,323 --> 00:24:21,053
<i>[Phone Rings]</i>

448
00:24:21,126 --> 00:24:25,324
Booth. Yeah? Yeah, I'm meeting
with them right now.

449
00:24:25,397 --> 00:24:28,491
- <i>Right. The one from the glove.</i>
- I'm sorry. I can't imagine...

450
00:24:28,567 --> 00:24:31,092
- Whose kid is this?
- Whose little girl is that?

451
00:24:31,169 --> 00:24:33,228
Are you sure? Thanks.

452
00:24:34,439 --> 00:24:36,236
- What?
- Um...

453
00:24:36,308 --> 00:24:38,868
<i>The print we found on</i>
<i>the rubber glove at the crime scene...</i>

454
00:24:38,944 --> 00:24:41,344
it doesn't match either wife.

455
00:24:41,413 --> 00:24:44,246
Oh, so it's back to square one.

456
00:24:44,316 --> 00:24:46,716
Are you sure I can't get
anyone a soda?

457
00:24:50,822 --> 00:24:52,756
Hey. Dr. Brennan, right?

458
00:24:52,824 --> 00:24:55,292
- Rebecca, hi.
- Is he in there?

459
00:24:55,360 --> 00:24:58,625
He is.
But it's not a good time.

460
00:24:58,697 --> 00:25:02,428
Not that my powers of discernment
have ever been particularly sharp...

461
00:25:02,501 --> 00:25:04,435
vis-à-vis good times from bad...

462
00:25:04,503 --> 00:25:07,097
but in this instance, it's bad.

463
00:25:07,172 --> 00:25:10,266
And I thought Seeley
was exaggerating about you.

464
00:25:10,342 --> 00:25:12,776
- With regard to...
- Just tell him to give me a call.

465
00:25:15,680 --> 00:25:17,978
Hey.

466
00:25:18,049 --> 00:25:20,040
Can I ask you something?

467
00:25:21,286 --> 00:25:24,084
- Why did you say no?
- Excuse me?

468
00:25:24,155 --> 00:25:27,989
When he asked you to marry him?
I mean, he seems an ideal candidate.

469
00:25:28,059 --> 00:25:30,755
Strong, alpha male,
good protective instincts.

470
00:25:30,829 --> 00:25:32,797
And I should discuss
this with you why?

471
00:25:32,864 --> 00:25:35,298
It's just...

472
00:25:35,367 --> 00:25:39,064
I'm not sure he knows.
And... I think it bothers him.

473
00:25:44,843 --> 00:25:47,038
I've always taken care of myself.

474
00:25:47,112 --> 00:25:49,478
To a fault sometimes.

475
00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:52,381
And when we got pregnant,
Seeley proposed.

476
00:25:52,450 --> 00:25:56,580
But I didn't want to be one of those
women who gets married out of need.

477
00:25:56,655 --> 00:25:59,453
So I said no.

478
00:25:59,524 --> 00:26:02,925
- I can see that.
- By the time that I realized I'd made a mistake...

479
00:26:02,994 --> 00:26:06,395
that I'd still
be the same person...

480
00:26:06,464 --> 00:26:09,490
I think there's a moment
for two people.

481
00:26:09,568 --> 00:26:14,301
A single moment where they
can either catch fire or...

482
00:26:15,707 --> 00:26:19,199
Seeley and I, we missed our moment.

483
00:26:19,277 --> 00:26:21,575
- Do you understand?
- I'm trying.

484
00:26:21,646 --> 00:26:24,843
But the "single moment" thesis
doesn't explain...

485
00:26:24,916 --> 00:26:27,214
Why we still get together.

486
00:26:27,285 --> 00:26:29,776
Fall together really.

487
00:26:29,854 --> 00:26:35,486
Because I think that we just
feel what used to be there.

488
00:26:35,560 --> 00:26:37,494
And we miss it.

489
00:26:37,562 --> 00:26:40,087
I think Booth thinks
you didn't marry him...

490
00:26:40,165 --> 00:26:42,156
because he wouldn't make
a good father.

491
00:26:42,233 --> 00:26:45,293
- What?
- He worries about it himself.

492
00:26:45,370 --> 00:26:48,999
What he does for a living.
His past as a sniper.

493
00:26:49,074 --> 00:26:51,065
Oh, God.

494
00:26:54,012 --> 00:26:57,846
Uh, do me a favor?
Don't tell him that I came by, okay?

495
00:26:57,916 --> 00:26:59,884
Please.

496
00:27:09,361 --> 00:27:13,354
<i>Man, what I would've given to have been</i>
<i>a fly on the wall when you told those wives.</i>

497
00:27:13,431 --> 00:27:15,524
You would've been swatted, trust me.

498
00:27:15,600 --> 00:27:19,058
No match on the prints from
our nationwide database either.

499
00:27:19,137 --> 00:27:21,731
At least we can assume our killer
was a first-time offender.

500
00:27:21,806 --> 00:27:23,865
Great. Thanks, Bones.
That narrows it down.

501
00:27:23,942 --> 00:27:26,342
So I hear you're back with your ex.

502
00:27:26,411 --> 00:27:28,743
- Don't look at me.
- <i>Your son must be thrilled.</i>

503
00:27:28,813 --> 00:27:32,681
I know I may thumb my nose at
the hypocrisy of marriage as a sacred institution.

504
00:27:32,751 --> 00:27:36,778
- <i>But I think a boy truly benefits...</i>
- I am not back with my ex.

505
00:27:36,855 --> 00:27:39,050
Let me finish.
A boy truly benefits...

506
00:27:39,124 --> 00:27:41,092
from knowing where
his parents stand, together or not.

507
00:27:41,159 --> 00:27:45,289
<i>Like I once had this dancer down in Miami</i>
<i>whose stage name was Abbey Road.</i>

508
00:27:45,363 --> 00:27:48,025
- Anyway, she had a kid too, right?
- That'll do, Ringo.

509
00:27:48,099 --> 00:27:51,364
- I think I scored, Dr. Brennan.
- Somebody just kill me right now.

510
00:27:51,436 --> 00:27:53,461
Dr. Saroyan sent me
back to the crime scene.

511
00:27:53,538 --> 00:27:56,701
That's a junction box with
a single brown hair embedded.

512
00:27:56,775 --> 00:28:00,108
- This is at floor level?
- Across from where the bathtub had been.

513
00:28:00,178 --> 00:28:02,976
You'll find its contours
match our trauma wound.

514
00:28:03,048 --> 00:28:05,141
Then let's see if this hair
is a match for Larry.

515
00:28:05,216 --> 00:28:09,050
Before you go, are we sure
these copper bits are from the tub?

516
00:28:09,120 --> 00:28:11,054
I assumed they'd come off
the fixtures.

517
00:28:11,122 --> 00:28:13,283
Yeah, but... but the drain,
the faucet and the spigots...

518
00:28:13,358 --> 00:28:16,623
- <i>they're all pristine outside a scratch or two.</i>
- Wait. Let me see that.

519
00:28:16,695 --> 00:28:19,391
It's bird shot.
Or it was.

520
00:28:19,464 --> 00:28:22,331
It's compressed copper that's frangible
so it breaks apart on impact.

521
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:26,496
- Could they kill a man?
- I think our vice president
disproved that possibility.

522
00:28:26,571 --> 00:28:29,267
Look, any ammo at
close range will do the job.

523
00:28:29,340 --> 00:28:31,774
But at the very least, a gunshot
would've sent Larry flying...

524
00:28:31,843 --> 00:28:33,902
causing his head to hit
this junction box.

525
00:28:33,978 --> 00:28:36,469
- Which given his condition...
- Would be fatal.

526
00:28:42,487 --> 00:28:45,615
Okay. What you thought
were teeth marks, Dr. Saroyan...

527
00:28:45,690 --> 00:28:48,682
<i>turned out to be Chinese characters</i>
<i>engraved along the side.</i>

528
00:28:48,760 --> 00:28:51,285
- What do they say?
- They say...

529
00:28:51,362 --> 00:28:54,490
"What make foolish man
think I speak Chinese?"

530
00:28:54,566 --> 00:28:56,534
I thought you were half Chinese?

531
00:28:56,601 --> 00:28:59,434
And I think you're half Swedish.
Let's hear some Swedish.

532
00:28:59,504 --> 00:29:02,166
What is it, Angela, please?

533
00:29:02,240 --> 00:29:04,868
It's a chopstick.
Only it's not the kind you eat with.

534
00:29:04,943 --> 00:29:08,344
- There's another kind?
- Well, you wouldn't comb your hair
with a fork, would you?

535
00:29:08,413 --> 00:29:10,847
- My hair?
- All right, look.

536
00:29:10,915 --> 00:29:14,214
The one character that
I was able to translate off the Internet...

537
00:29:14,285 --> 00:29:17,152
is the word "beauty,"
and I realized it's meant for hair.

538
00:29:17,222 --> 00:29:20,885
<i>Where you twist it in a bun</i>
<i>and stick this through to hold it in place?</i>

539
00:29:20,959 --> 00:29:24,986
But if that's what this is,
we can be pretty sure it wasn't Larry's.

540
00:29:26,865 --> 00:29:30,961
<i>Thanks. Roommate says she went to go meet</i>
<i>some friends at the Beltway Burger.</i>

541
00:29:31,035 --> 00:29:33,299
And you think
it's this Chloe girl because...

542
00:29:33,371 --> 00:29:36,363
Of the chopsticks, right?
As soon as Cam said it, I knew it.

543
00:29:36,441 --> 00:29:39,467
Because when I went to go see Pete,
she had chopsticks in the back of her hair.

544
00:29:39,544 --> 00:29:42,012
- And how did Hodgins find out?
- I'm sorry?

545
00:29:42,080 --> 00:29:44,708
- "Yeah, I hear you're back with your ex."
- I don't know.

546
00:29:44,783 --> 00:29:48,082
I assume it was Cam. I was only trying
to engage her in social intercourse.

547
00:29:48,153 --> 00:29:50,519
- Excuse me?
- Just trying to be normal.

548
00:29:50,588 --> 00:29:53,216
Congenial exchange with a coworker.

549
00:29:53,291 --> 00:29:55,418
And if that's what gossip is,
I don't like it at all.

550
00:29:55,493 --> 00:29:57,859
Yeah, you think you don't like it?
I can't stand...

551
00:29:57,929 --> 00:30:00,693
There it is. Beltway Burger.
[Clears Throat]

552
00:30:00,765 --> 00:30:03,563
- <i>[Horn Honking]</i>
- <i># [Rock]</i>

553
00:30:10,475 --> 00:30:13,035
# [Continues Over Headphones]

554
00:30:18,950 --> 00:30:20,850
Hey, Chloe.
Meetin' some friends?

555
00:30:20,919 --> 00:30:23,717
Oh, hi!
You're that F.B.I. guy!

556
00:30:25,990 --> 00:30:27,958
Yes, I'm the F.B.I. guy.

557
00:30:28,026 --> 00:30:30,927
So you worship at the temple
of Beltway Burger too, huh?

558
00:30:30,995 --> 00:30:34,192
- Yeah, on occasion.
- Yeah, I may be 90% vegetarian...

559
00:30:34,265 --> 00:30:36,790
but their burgers...
can't get enough of'em lately.

560
00:30:36,868 --> 00:30:40,235
- How many weeks are you?
- Excuse me?

561
00:30:40,305 --> 00:30:43,103
Pregnant. I could tell by your gait.

562
00:30:43,174 --> 00:30:47,076
<i>Your ilia... they've already started</i>
<i>shifting to widen the birth canal.</i>

563
00:30:47,145 --> 00:30:49,477
- You can tell that?
- So you are pregnant?

564
00:30:49,547 --> 00:30:51,447
Fourteen weeks.

565
00:30:51,516 --> 00:30:53,609
- Booth...
- <i>[Footsteps Approaching]</i>

566
00:30:53,685 --> 00:30:55,619
- <i>Chloe's friends.</i>
- [Chattering]

567
00:30:55,687 --> 00:30:58,952
<i>Chloe's friends. Taking the kids</i>
<i>out for a little late night snack, ladies?</i>

568
00:31:00,825 --> 00:31:03,385
<i>Don't tell me.</i>
<i>Larry's the father.</i>

569
00:31:03,461 --> 00:31:05,088
[Sighs]

570
00:31:14,472 --> 00:31:17,737
There's a playground about
halfway between Gayle and me...

571
00:31:17,809 --> 00:31:19,743
designed for kids
with special needs.

572
00:31:19,811 --> 00:31:22,575
Rubber surfacing, high-back swings.

573
00:31:22,647 --> 00:31:25,878
I took Ray there last week,
and Lila was there with Jenny.

574
00:31:25,950 --> 00:31:28,043
The kids started playing.
We started talking.

575
00:31:28,119 --> 00:31:31,350
- And one topic led to another.
- And... small world.

576
00:31:31,422 --> 00:31:34,755
- Yeah, too small.
- What about Chloe?

577
00:31:34,826 --> 00:31:39,661
Well, after we got over the initial shock,
like yesterday but real...

578
00:31:39,731 --> 00:31:42,928
we decided to follow Larry
to work the next morning...

579
00:31:43,001 --> 00:31:44,798
straight to a motel
where Chloe was waiting.

580
00:31:44,869 --> 00:31:47,565
<i>And if that wasn't enough to</i>
<i>make our heads explode...</i>

581
00:31:47,639 --> 00:31:50,870
we then had to find out
about Chloe's... condition.

582
00:31:50,942 --> 00:31:53,775
At which point, you knew it was
time to confront Larry.

583
00:31:53,845 --> 00:31:57,337
- I had no idea that Larry was married.
- Let alone twice.

584
00:31:57,415 --> 00:32:00,282
But since your prints match the one
left in the rubber glove...

585
00:32:00,351 --> 00:32:02,478
we assume it wasn't long
before you found out.

586
00:32:02,553 --> 00:32:04,851
We checked your
phone records, Gayle, and, uh...

587
00:32:04,923 --> 00:32:08,290
<i>you didn't leave Larry any</i>
<i>messages after Friday night.</i>

588
00:32:08,359 --> 00:32:10,554
The night you, Lila, and Chloe...

589
00:32:10,628 --> 00:32:13,688
told him you were going to
see him together to get answers.

590
00:32:13,765 --> 00:32:17,030
So you found Larry at his job.
You shot him point-blank.

591
00:32:17,101 --> 00:32:19,831
<i>And you dragged his sorry ass</i>
<i>back to the bathtub.</i>

592
00:32:19,904 --> 00:32:23,533
Where you doused him in
sodium hypochlorite, calcium hypochlorite.

593
00:32:23,608 --> 00:32:27,738
Or as you and I like to call 'em,
bleach and Quickie Plumber.

594
00:32:27,812 --> 00:32:30,042
Which, as an eighth-grade teacher,
you knew would do the trick.

595
00:32:30,114 --> 00:32:33,811
- Simple earth science.
- Look, all that's true. But we didn't kill him.

596
00:32:33,885 --> 00:32:36,376
- Really? Then who did?
- He killed himself.

597
00:32:36,454 --> 00:32:38,388
- He killed himself.
- He killed himself.

598
00:32:39,824 --> 00:32:42,258
Larry was dead when you got there?

599
00:32:42,327 --> 00:32:44,522
- On the bathroom floor.
- The gun was still in his mouth.

600
00:32:44,595 --> 00:32:47,257
The coward must've freaked at the thought
of facing us together.

601
00:32:47,332 --> 00:32:49,095
If we'd surprised him,
maybe he'd still be alive.

602
00:32:49,167 --> 00:32:53,263
<i>Back up. You're saying</i>
<i>that the gun was still in his mouth?</i>

603
00:32:53,338 --> 00:32:55,863
His finger was on the trigger.
It was awful.

604
00:32:55,940 --> 00:32:58,704
And where's the gun now?

605
00:32:58,776 --> 00:33:01,210
I buried it in my backyard.

606
00:33:01,279 --> 00:33:03,372
That's a good place for it.

607
00:33:07,418 --> 00:33:09,010
- Unbelievable.
- Yeah, you got that right.

608
00:33:09,087 --> 00:33:10,748
- You know what? They're lying.
- How do you know?

609
00:33:10,822 --> 00:33:12,551
Oh, come on. They've been
lying since day one.

610
00:33:12,623 --> 00:33:15,057
Between all of them, they should have
a dozen Oscars by now.

611
00:33:15,126 --> 00:33:17,356
- I know what those are.
- I mean, come on. Suicide? Mm-mmm.

612
00:33:17,428 --> 00:33:19,658
Bird shot or not, okay,
every self-inflicted I've seen...

613
00:33:19,731 --> 00:33:21,665
the guy shoots himself,
and he drops the gun.

614
00:33:21,733 --> 00:33:23,826
Right? It's an automatic reaction.
Bang, drop.

615
00:33:23,901 --> 00:33:25,960
There's no way the gun
ends up in his mouth.

616
00:33:26,037 --> 00:33:28,130
Then we'd better go dig up that gun.

617
00:33:28,206 --> 00:33:31,334
- Seeley?
- I'll get the ball rolling.

618
00:33:33,411 --> 00:33:35,709
- Was that Dr. Brennan?
- Uh-huh.

619
00:33:35,780 --> 00:33:37,714
Why are you here?

620
00:33:37,782 --> 00:33:40,910
I needed to know if you were gonna
coach Parker's T-ball team this year.

621
00:33:40,985 --> 00:33:43,920
- You know I always coach Parker's T-ball team.
- I didn't wanna assume...

622
00:33:43,988 --> 00:33:46,786
Okay, whoa. What is going
on here, Rebecca? Okay?

623
00:33:46,858 --> 00:33:48,792
Because, look,
I thought we agreed here.

624
00:33:48,860 --> 00:33:51,829
We cannot end up groping each other
in the F.B.I. closet.

625
00:33:51,896 --> 00:33:54,490
We can't do that.
We're done.

626
00:33:54,565 --> 00:33:58,092
- I know.
- Really?

627
00:33:58,169 --> 00:34:02,299
Seeley, all the excuses
I gave you for not wanting to get married...

628
00:34:02,373 --> 00:34:05,069
- my independence, your work...
- I know.

629
00:34:05,143 --> 00:34:07,134
No, you don't.

630
00:34:09,280 --> 00:34:11,908
You are a wonderful father.

631
00:34:14,385 --> 00:34:17,354
And Parker is a lucky kid.

632
00:34:17,422 --> 00:34:19,856
Such a lucky kid.

633
00:34:21,559 --> 00:34:25,859
And obviously, we still have
feelings for each other.

634
00:34:29,267 --> 00:34:31,667
Do you still wanna marry me?

635
00:34:33,037 --> 00:34:34,971
Rebecca...

636
00:34:36,774 --> 00:34:39,174
No, I don't.

637
00:34:41,212 --> 00:34:43,180
I don't wanna marry you either.

638
00:34:49,454 --> 00:34:51,854
Here are the forms for T-ball.

639
00:34:53,658 --> 00:34:55,956
- I'll miss you.
- Yeah.

640
00:34:56,027 --> 00:34:58,120
And I'm gonna miss you too.

641
00:34:58,196 --> 00:35:01,063
You know what I'm gonna
miss the most?

642
00:35:02,934 --> 00:35:05,129
Yeah. But let's not go there.

643
00:35:20,551 --> 00:35:22,644
<i>Okay. DNA on the barrel...</i>

644
00:35:22,720 --> 00:35:25,280
confirms it was in
Larry's mouth at some point.

645
00:35:25,356 --> 00:35:27,290
Yeah. Well, I still don't buy it.

646
00:35:27,358 --> 00:35:29,485
You know, the kickback alone
would've forced it out.

647
00:35:29,560 --> 00:35:31,926
Unless he was dead before the shot.

648
00:35:31,996 --> 00:35:34,760
Well, yeah, that's true.
But, uh...

649
00:35:34,832 --> 00:35:38,495
- Wait, what?
- The inside of Larry's skull is pitted...

650
00:35:38,569 --> 00:35:41,231
which I had always attributed
to the effects of the lye.

651
00:35:41,305 --> 00:35:44,741
But each tiny hole matches
perfectly with the bird shot...

652
00:35:44,809 --> 00:35:46,674
right down to these
specks of copper.

653
00:35:46,744 --> 00:35:48,439
Are you saying that it was suicide?

654
00:35:48,513 --> 00:35:52,176
I would, except these holes
are void of blood...

655
00:35:52,250 --> 00:35:56,380
which would suggest they were inflicted after
blood stopped pumping trough Larry's head.

656
00:35:56,454 --> 00:35:58,388
No, keep talking.
I'll catch up.

657
00:35:58,456 --> 00:36:02,290
Well, unlike this blunt force trauma...
no shortage of blood here.

658
00:36:02,360 --> 00:36:05,591
Proving he was dead
before he was shot.

659
00:36:05,663 --> 00:36:10,896
So now we're talking about
a faked homicide to cover up a faked suicide?

660
00:36:10,968 --> 00:36:14,734
A faked suicide meant to cover up
